FEMALE SPEAKER: Welcome.

00:00:03.540 --> 00:00:04.900
Welcome to today's talk.

00:00:04.900 --> 00:00:05.872
I'm Rachel Amara.

00:00:05.872 --> 00:00:07.830
I'm actually based in
our San Francisco office,

00:00:07.830 --> 00:00:10.482
but I like to have good excuses
to come down to Mountain View

00:00:10.482 --> 00:00:11.940
every now and then
and host authors

00:00:11.940 --> 00:00:14.430
here or in San Francisco.

00:00:14.430 --> 00:00:18.450
So today I'm really excited to
host Jonathan Robinson, whose

00:00:18.450 --> 00:00:20.870
joining us here from
the world of the Bay

00:00:20.870 --> 00:00:23.490
Area in northern California.

00:00:23.490 --> 00:00:25.690
Jonathan is here to talk
today about his book

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:28.240
"Find Happiness
Now," and he's got

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:30.790
a great hour planned for
us, which includes things

00:00:30.790 --> 00:00:35.650
like music and sound effects
and magic tricks and all kinds

00:00:35.650 --> 00:00:38.380
of tips on what we
really need and need

00:00:38.380 --> 00:00:40.850
to find to be happy now.

00:00:40.850 --> 00:00:44.850
So just a quick
update on Jonathan--

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:46.350
so Jonathan's written
over 10 books.

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:48.770
So he is only talking
about, really, one here,

00:00:48.770 --> 00:00:52.100
but there's another book here
called "Life's Big Questions"

00:00:52.100 --> 00:00:54.650
that some of you have
gotten, and there

00:00:54.650 --> 00:00:58.350
is additional books
in his repertoire.

00:00:58.350 --> 00:01:02.150
They've been translated in
over 47 languages total,

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:08.490
and he has been-- over 250
million people have reached

00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:10.500
and have been
through the programs,

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:12.720
whether he's been
seen on Oprah or CNN

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:15.430
or reading books or things
like this Google Talk.

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:17.930
So please welcome
Jonathan Robinson.

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:19.763
Join me to welcome him.

00:01:19.763 --> 00:01:23.470
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:25.440
JONATHAN ROBINSON: Thank
you for coming today.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:27.750
I'm going to begin with
a provocative question,

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:30.260
and that is if you
could download something

00:01:30.260 --> 00:01:33.950
on your smartphone, an
app that could stimulate

00:01:33.950 --> 00:01:38.830
your brain to feelings
of ecstasy and happiness,

00:01:38.830 --> 00:01:41.050
would you plug into
that technology?

00:01:41.050 --> 00:01:43.080
How many people would-- yeah?

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:44.519
How many people would not?

00:01:44.519 --> 00:01:46.810
And how many people will not
raise their hand no matter

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:48.200
what I ask.

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:48.700
A couple.

00:01:48.700 --> 00:01:50.830
Yeah, OK, great.

00:01:50.830 --> 00:01:52.680
We may be in a position
where we actually

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:55.300
have to make decisions
like that soon

00:01:55.300 --> 00:01:59.030
because the future
technology of happiness

00:01:59.030 --> 00:02:01.860
is happening very
quickly, and I'm

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:05.210
going to give you a tour of what
some of those technologies are.

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:07.770
But before I go into
what the future is,

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:11.020
I want to talk about how
to find happiness now,

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:14.200
and all you need is what's
the magical substance

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:17.090
between your own ears, OK?

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:19.650
So we may have
different terms for it,

00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:23.760
but I think everything that we
are doing is to be happier now

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:27.450
or in the future,
whether you are trying

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:29.810
to get a lot of money
so you can be happy

00:02:29.810 --> 00:02:32.410
or a relationship
so you can be happy.

00:02:32.410 --> 00:02:35.492
That is what we're basically
doing all the time.

00:02:35.492 --> 00:02:37.200
Now you may have a
different name for it.

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:42.070
You might call it peace of
mind or contentment or life

00:02:42.070 --> 00:02:44.120
satisfaction.

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:46.440
But the reason you
came to work today

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:48.470
is because you think
that by doing that,

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:51.294
it's going to make you
happier in the future.

00:02:51.294 --> 00:02:52.710
I'll remind you,
if you have kids,

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:55.550
the reason you had kids is
because you think someday they

00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:58.880
will help make you happier
in the future, right?

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:01.550
So that's what
we're always doing,

00:03:01.550 --> 00:03:03.970
but I have good
news and bad news.

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:06.590
And the bad news is
that we're really not

00:03:06.590 --> 00:03:09.430
very good at this skill.

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:13.980
In the last 100 years,
our ability to be happy

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:19.890
has not gone up at all and
yet the level of depression

00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:23.900
has risen by a factor of
10 in the last 60 years.

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:26.690
Right now, 10% of Americans
are clinically depressed.

00:03:29.350 --> 00:03:31.130
So it's an important
skill to learn

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:32.963
since that's what we're
always trying to do.

00:03:32.963 --> 00:03:36.100
Whatever your method is, whether
it be money or relationships

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:38.660
or meditation or
yoga, you're always

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:41.880
trying to get to this
magical state of contentment,

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:44.027
and we really are bad at it.

00:03:44.027 --> 00:03:45.610
So there's a lot
room for improvement,

00:03:45.610 --> 00:03:47.270
and I think that's good news.

00:03:47.270 --> 00:03:50.180
And part of the
good news is knowing

00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:55.336
that it is a learnable
skill, but technology

00:03:55.336 --> 00:03:56.460
doesn't seem to be helping.

00:03:56.460 --> 00:03:59.760
So we have to ask ourselves,
is technology helping us?

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:03.450
We think technology is here
to make our lives better.

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:07.130
And in fact, I am very grateful
to Google and my smartphone

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:09.060
and everything else.

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:12.260
But for a lot of people,
the technology actually

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:16.144
ends up being WMDs-- not
weapons of mass destruction,

00:04:16.144 --> 00:04:19.959
but widgets of mass distraction.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:25.210
The average person watches four
and a half hours of TV a day.

00:04:25.210 --> 00:04:27.710
I watch almost none, which
means that some guy in Iowa

00:04:27.710 --> 00:04:30.780
has to watch nine hours
to make up for me.

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:33.260
Sometimes I turn on the TV
so that guy can step outside

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:36.780
for a few minutes, you know?

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:39.170
So we have to learn
how to use technology

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:41.800
since we're surrounded
by it to actually boost

00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:43.590
our level of happiness
rather than boost

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:48.110
our level of distraction,
and that is a skill as well.

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:53.280
So we are taught in
the American cult-ure--

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:59.010
the American cult-ure-- that
success leads to happiness.

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:01.330
Does Donald Trump look
that happy to you?

00:05:01.330 --> 00:05:04.550
If success led to happiness,
he would be a pretty happy guy,

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:05.590
right?

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:06.809
He does not look that happy.

00:05:06.809 --> 00:05:07.350
I've met him.

00:05:07.350 --> 00:05:09.290
He's not.

00:05:09.290 --> 00:05:14.310
But the opposite is true--
happiness does lead to success.

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:18.000
Happy people make $750,000 more
over the course of their life

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.560
than unhappy people.

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:21.570
They live nine years longer.

00:05:21.570 --> 00:05:24.360
There's no pill you can
take that will help you live

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:28.950
nine years longer, but
happiness actually can do that.

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:32.350
Happy people raise happier kids.

00:05:32.350 --> 00:05:35.250
They take fewer sick days.

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:37.590
Corporations pay me to
talk about happiness

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:41.010
because it helps their bottom
line in that people become

00:05:41.010 --> 00:05:42.640
more productive.

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:45.360
They also take fewer sick days.

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:48.400
So there's a lot of
benefits to being happy,

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:49.910
and it's not
something that is just

00:05:49.910 --> 00:05:52.590
a feel good thing that
makes you more selfish.

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:57.410
In fact, happy people are more
giving than unhappy people.

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:00.180
So it's very important that
people learn this skill

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:02.000
and learn healthy
ways of doing it

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.860
so that everybody
benefits from it.

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:11.960
Now the first key in terms
of the skill of happiness

00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:15.820
is being able to know what your
target is, having it defined,

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:18.170
because people define
happiness very differently.

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:24.910
For some people, it is a life of
total serenity and relaxation.

00:06:24.910 --> 00:06:29.210
For other people, it's total
adrenaline and facing fears

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:31.140
and going for an adventure.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.950
Those are very
different things, so you

00:06:32.950 --> 00:06:36.790
want to know what your specific
target is because that will

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:39.940
give you a better chance
of hitting that target.

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:43.140
I learned the importance
of knowing your target

00:06:43.140 --> 00:06:44.820
when I was a
freshman in college.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:48.130
My roommate was one of the
best basketball players in LA,

00:06:48.130 --> 00:06:50.820
and he challenged me to
a game of basketball.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.040
We put some money on it.

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:54.900
And I said, I'll play you
a game on one condition--

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:57.850
I can bring out any 1-ounce
gadget onto the court

00:06:57.850 --> 00:06:59.900
and place it wherever I want.

00:06:59.900 --> 00:07:00.730
He said, OK.

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:02.250
He knew he'd beat me.

00:07:02.250 --> 00:07:04.424
So I brought out
this 1-ounce gadget.

00:07:04.424 --> 00:07:06.340
Looked a little bit like
this. and I placed it

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:10.105
in a strategic location,
namely over his eyes.

00:07:10.105 --> 00:07:11.750
And I said, let the games begin.

00:07:14.570 --> 00:07:17.750
Now admittedly, it was
still pretty close,

00:07:17.750 --> 00:07:19.980
but I beat one of the best
basketball players in LA

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:22.270
because I knew exactly
what I was aiming for.

00:07:22.270 --> 00:07:24.440
The fact that I had
total lack of skill

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:28.460
was not as important as
knowing where the target was.

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:31.030
So you don't want to climb
the ladder success only

00:07:31.030 --> 00:07:33.470
to find it's against
the wrong wall.

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:36.550
What is happiness to you?

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:38.580
What does it look like?

00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:41.740
Because if you don't define it,
your parents' vision of it will

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:46.560
define it for you or the
American "cult"-ure will define

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:47.260
it for you.

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:49.880
And American culture
says that happiness

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:52.370
equals a lot of money.

00:07:52.370 --> 00:07:54.460
But people who are
rich are no happier

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:56.870
than people who are
middle class, so it's

00:07:56.870 --> 00:07:59.370
good to define these things.

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:01.990
A second key, which
you probably heard of,

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:04.510
is to practice gratitude.

00:08:04.510 --> 00:08:05.970
Now we've all
heard that, but you

00:08:05.970 --> 00:08:08.630
need a really good,
simple technique.

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:11.590
So in the '90s, I
interviewed a lot

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:15.247
of well known spiritual
leaders for a book I was doing.

00:08:15.247 --> 00:08:17.580
I interviewed everybody from
Mother Teresa-- late Mother

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.920
Teresa-- to Dalai
Lama and Deepak Chopra

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:21.480
and Wayne Dyer and
all those people.

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:23.560
And I was asking
them for their best

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:26.480
method for finding
happiness and for finding

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:28.470
a spiritual connection.

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:30.310
And I was amazed
at how many of them

00:08:30.310 --> 00:08:33.549
said that gratitude was a key.

00:08:33.549 --> 00:08:37.270
So a few years later when I'd
heard of an Indian guru who

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:41.330
supposedly had this magical
mantra for helping people

00:08:41.330 --> 00:08:43.740
experience
overwhelming gratitude,

00:08:43.740 --> 00:08:45.880
I wanted to know
what that mantra was.

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:51.030
So I travelled 18,000 miles
to India to talk to this guy.

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:52.690
And if you've ever
been to India,

00:08:52.690 --> 00:08:55.090
it is not an easy
place to travel to.

00:08:55.090 --> 00:08:58.330
And then when I got there, going
on a rickshaw for three hours.

00:08:58.330 --> 00:09:00.950
Then I get to the
ashram and I have

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:04.120
to wait in line four
hours to talk to the guru.

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:06.300
Finally I get to him
and I say, guru, gee,

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:09.040
I came all the way from America
to learn your magical mantra

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:10.520
to feel overwhelming gratitude.

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:12.710
Please tell me.

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:16.130
So he says-- his
deep Indian accent--

00:09:16.130 --> 00:09:20.330
ah yes, my mantra is the most
powerful mantra on Earth.

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:22.350
Said, normally I don't
say it so quickly,

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:24.040
but you travel all
the way from America.

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:26.400
I will tell you the mantra.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:27.250
I'm very excited.

00:09:27.250 --> 00:09:29.130
And he leans in to
whisper into my ear

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:33.670
and he says, whenever possible,
repeat the following words.

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:41.820
The mantra I give you are
the words "thank you."

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:43.750
I go, that's it?

00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:45.690
Thank you?

00:09:45.690 --> 00:09:48.690
I travel 18,000 miles
for thank-- that's it?

00:09:48.690 --> 00:09:52.330
He says, no, "that's it" is
a mantra you had been using.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:54.490
That makes you feel like
you never have enough.

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:57.804
My mantra is "thank you,"
not "that's it." "That's it"

00:09:57.804 --> 00:09:58.720
will take you nowhere.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:07.180
Well, I was disappointed
and pretty pissed off,

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:10.750
but I figure I'd traveled so
far I would do what he said,

00:10:10.750 --> 00:10:12.560
so I told them thank you.

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:15.040
He said, no, you
can't say thank you.

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:19.170
You have to say thank you from
your heart many times a day

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:22.460
for each of the
life's blessings.

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:23.070
So I tried.

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:24.630
I said thank you,
and I left there.

00:10:24.630 --> 00:10:27.082
And I took a taxi, and
as I'm entering the taxi,

00:10:27.082 --> 00:10:28.840
I noticed it has
air conditioning.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:31.280
It's about 105 degrees in India.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:35.510
I said, oh, well, thank you
for the air conditioning.

00:10:35.510 --> 00:10:38.850
And then I leave the taxi and
I put my hand in my pocket.

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:40.270
I have money.

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:42.200
Thank you for my money.

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:45.190
Then I go to the hotel room, and
there's a bottle of clean water

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:46.020
there.

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:48.260
Thank you for the clean water.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:50.520
And then there's a
nice toilet there.

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:53.460
In India, good toilets
can be hard to find.

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:55.190
Thank you for the toilet.

00:10:55.190 --> 00:10:57.182
And then there was air
conditioning in the room

00:10:57.182 --> 00:10:58.140
and there was a shower.

00:10:58.140 --> 00:10:59.970
I took a shower.

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:02.570
Thank you for the shower.

00:11:02.570 --> 00:11:07.860
And in this hotel, there
was actually Wi-Fi in India.

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:09.470
I was very thankful for that.

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:11.930
Get on the computer, Google.

00:11:11.930 --> 00:11:14.102
Thank you for Google.

00:11:14.102 --> 00:11:17.480
Oh, I feel that
many times a day.

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:21.140
And then on and on it went.

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:24.670
And within about an hour, I had
tears of gratitude going down

00:11:24.670 --> 00:11:29.920
my face because we live
better than billionaires

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:32.370
lived 20 years ago.

00:11:32.370 --> 00:11:34.300
We have access to all
the world's information

00:11:34.300 --> 00:11:35.660
in our phone.

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:38.800
We can talk to anyone in
the world from anywhere

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:40.120
in the world.

00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:43.700
We-- for god's sakes, we have
Ben and Jerry's and Haagen Dazs

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:45.870
ice cream never more
than two miles away.

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:48.370
Life is good, right?

00:11:48.370 --> 00:11:50.740
But if you don't
have a simple method

00:11:50.740 --> 00:11:56.139
for feeling that gratitude,
it all goes by unnoticed.

00:11:56.139 --> 00:11:57.930
I mean, how many days
do we do that that we

00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:01.670
have all these blessings
and they're invisible to us?

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:03.740
So a simple method
like saying thank you

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:06.380
from your heart for the
people in your life--

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:08.966
even the people that
cause you trouble.

00:12:08.966 --> 00:12:10.340
If it weren't for
jerks like you,

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:11.464
I wouldn't know compassion.

00:12:15.025 --> 00:12:15.524
Thank you.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:21.660
So a simple method like that can
help you tune into gratitude.

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:23.610
And we're all so busy
nowadays that it's

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:27.360
nice to have methods that
don't require any extra time.

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:29.460
You're already taking a shower.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:31.470
You're already eating
Haagen Dazs ice cream.

00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:35.310
You're already eating free food.

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:38.050
It just takes a moment
to feel those blessings.

00:12:38.050 --> 00:12:39.620
So that's a second key.

00:12:39.620 --> 00:12:43.640
A third key is to learn
easy ways to be happy.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:46.320
A lot of people in my parents'
generation, their method

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:49.590
